have all the answers. But we hope to give
you an idea of the direction and the motivations

00:03:42.380 --> 00:03:50.229
behind what we're doing. Okay. So ground zero;
from the user's perspective, what are web

00:03:50.229 --> 00:03:56.310
apps. Well, you know, I think everybody in
this room knows but, you know, we know it

00:03:56.310 --> 00:04:02.759
when we see it, right? It's Gmail, it's maps,
it's mint.com, it's Pandora. Basically, it's

00:04:02.759 --> 00:04:07.840
rich applications that are built using web
technologies designed to run in a web browser,

00:04:07.840 --> 00:04:13.810
right? Their data tends to be stored in a
Cloud and that means it's available everywhere.

00:04:13.810 --> 00:04:18.480
So, your home computer, your work computer,
your phone on the go; it's ubiquitous. It

00:04:18.480 --> 00:04:25.130
doesn't matter what operating system, what
device you're using. The web is truly everywhere.

00:04:25.130 --> 00:04:31.500
But from a user perspective, web apps can
be hard to find. You know, the first problem,

00:04:31.500 --> 00:04:37.140
before we even get to finding them is just
knowing that they exist. Awareness is a big

00:04:37.140 --> 00:04:42.210
deal. I mean, I'm sure, you've all had this
experience. I have myself of--you've been

00:04:42.210 --> 00:04:46.540
using some cool web app and you show it to
a friend, you know, family member or whatever

00:04:46.540 --> 00:04:51.450
and they go, "Oh, my god. What's that? I had
no clue that something like that even existed.

00:04:51.450 --> 00:04:57.320
Why didn't anybody tell me?" And there's a
lot of these things that are out there that

00:04:57.320 --> 00:05:03.840
just don't get the attention they should.
Part of this is because there are no authoritative

00:05:03.840 --> 00:05:10.010
sources for web apps. There's no place you'd
go that shows you what are the good ones,

00:05:10.010 --> 00:05:14.780
right? What are the ones that users use the
most, that they reviewed the best? What are

00:05:14.780 --> 00:05:20.400
the ones that are going to help me the most?
You heard some examples in the keynote about

00:05:20.400 --> 00:05:26.420
trying to find your, you know, a particular
game that you're interested in and how--the

00:05:26.420 --> 00:05:32.162
fact that you can find them but you don't
know which ones are, you know, you don't see

00:05:32.162 --> 00:05:36.510
reviews intermixed, you don't see popularity
intermixed. And, in fact, it's a little worse

00:05:36.510 --> 00:05:41.560
than that and that you'll often see things
that are, you know, platform specific or device

00:05:41.560 --> 00:05:49.010
specific mixed in with the web apps that are--that
you're trying to find. So on top of that,

00:05:49.010 --> 00:05:54.170
you know, the apps themselves don't actually
do a lot to help search engines, you know,

00:05:54.170 --> 00:05:59.630
find them. Part of this is just due to the
nature of what is an app. An app is not necessarily

00:05:59.630 --> 00:06:05.100
content itself but it contains other content
and often the content it contains is personal,

00:06:05.100 --> 00:06:11.150
it's private to yourself. So, that content
might not be crawlable. The web apps don't

00:06:11.150 --> 00:06:16.700
necessarily have a lot of information to crawl
that describes what they are that helps the

00:06:16.700 --> 00:06:24.740
search engines reinforce what's, you know,
the normal tricks that they use to find things.

00:06:24.740 --> 00:06:29.090
So when you find an app or web app out there,
you know, most of them you'll find are free

00:06:29.090 --> 00:06:34.120
or ad supported, but, occasionally, you'll
find some that people charge money for, and

00:06:34.120 --> 00:06:41.990
that--they tend to have a pretty poor experience.
Part of the reason is because as a user, you

00:06:41.990 --> 00:06:46.580
know, when you come across, you know, a web
form that says, "Okay, I want to buy something

00:06:46.580 --> 00:06:51.770
on the web." You know, regardless of what
it is, there's an immediate question of trust.

00:06:51.770 --> 00:06:57.780
First of, who are these guys? Now, a lot of
web apps are being built by small, unknown

00:06:57.780 --> 00:07:02.770
companies. These are things that, you know,
people haven't heard of before, and giving

00:07:02.770 --> 00:07:06.830
over your credit card information, your personal
information requires a certain amount of trust.

00:07:06.830 --> 00:07:11.800
So, there's the hesitation, should I do this,
and that you'll lose some number of users

00:07:11.800 --> 00:07:16.520
just from trust right there. The next thing
is that actually filling out your payment

00:07:16.520 --> 00:07:21.770
information as inconvenient. It can be multiple
pages of forms just to be able to buy a really

00:07:21.770 --> 00:07:27.330
simple thing. And the ironic thing about this
is that, the cheaper, you know, the purchase

00:07:27.330 --> 00:07:33.070
is the more likely that those trust and inconvenience
issues actually get in the way and make it--so

00:07:33.070 --> 00:07:38.370
you say, "Ah, I'm not going to bother. It's
just, you know, a $5 thing or a $10, it's

00:07:38.370 --> 00:07:47.380
not worth my time." So, okay, so now you've--let's
say you get a web app. You know, we've gotten

00:07:47.380 --> 00:07:54.580
pass some of those hard to find, hard to buy
questions, but once you'll get a web app when

00:07:54.580 --> 00:08:02.590
there--if you look at how they interact with
browsers today, it's not ideal. Web apps sort

00:08:02.590 --> 00:08:08.450
of by definition are special to users. These
are the things where you've got your data

00:08:08.450 --> 00:08:14.550
in, your time in; you have--you're using it
as, you know, day-to-day stuff. It's important

00:08:14.550 --> 00:08:20.461
to you. But the browser doesn't make it particularly
important. It treats it just like any other--any

00:08:20.461 --> 00:08:26.130
old page. So if you look at, you know, this
browser here, you know, can you tell which

00:08:26.130 --> 00:08:30.180
ones are the web apps, which are ones are
the ones that are important to me, you know.

00:08:30.180 --> 00:08:35.120
Now, some of you might recognize a few of
the icons, but as you get a lot more tabs

00:08:35.120 --> 00:08:44.720
even that becomes hard to find. You know,
further, you know, a lot of these apps, if

00:08:44.720 --> 00:08:49.540
you compare them in to desktop apps, they're
missing a lot of functionality that you come

00:08:49.540 --> 00:08:52.860
to expect. They don't have deep OS integration.
They don't have, you know, a shortcut to launch

00:08:52.860 --> 00:09:01.920
it. They don't have an entry to in the taskbar
to dock. They don't have fast apps switching.

00:09:01.920 --> 00:09:07.310
They can't open document types. They don't
have access to a lot of the underlying capabilities

00:09:07.310 --> 00:09:14.450
that you're used to at seeing in normal desktop
apps. And they're not trusted to take--to

00:09:14.450 --> 00:09:19.900
use that functionality. And the--part of the
reason is because of the trust model, the

00:09:19.900 --> 00:09:25.990
security model in the Web. The nice thing
about the security model in the Web is it's

00:09:25.990 --> 00:09:31.529
set up in such a way that you can click on
a link, any old link and not really worry

00:09:31.529 --> 00:09:35.580
too much about it. This is different from
desktop applications where if you run any

00:09:35.580 --> 00:09:40.150
old desktop application, you know, who knows
what's going to happen to your computer, you

00:09:40.150 --> 00:09:45.230
know, versus with all the spyware and malware
and whatever out there. But in general, clicking

00:09:45.230 --> 00:09:49.860
on a link at a web browser should be safe.
You should be able to trust that it does something

00:09:49.860 --> 00:09:55.610
reasonable. But part of that trust, part of
that security model enforces limited capabilities.

00:09:55.610 --> 00:10:01.481
And in the case where we have web apps that
we trust that we know, we want them to do

00:10:01.481 --> 00:10:09.140
more, the web apps, the web security model
gets in the way of that. Okay. Let's see if

00:10:09.140 --> 00:10:20.730
we can improve some things. We're going to
get a demo together here. Let's see if the

00:10:20.730 --> 00:10:34.149
technology cooperates with us. Okay. Okay.
